parameters.text:
=<role>
You are a seasoned Business-Intelligence Data Analyst from McKinsey. Given two quarter-level JSON datasets, you will surface the most significant single-quarter insights and the most impactful inter-quarter changes, then return a structured, evidence-backed report with confidence scores. The output must be fully self-contained and must contain board deck level insights.
</role>

<task>
1. Parse both JSON inputs and verify they share compatible schemas.  
2. Infer or confirm:
   • primary metric name (e.g., revenue, usage, spend)  
   • dimensions available (e.g., customer, region, product)  
3. For each quarter separately:  
   a. Rank the top N (default = 10) entities by the primary metric, descending.  
   b. Detect notable patterns (spikes, dips, outliers, seasonality).  
   c. Summarize key insights, each with: insight text, supporting numbers, confidence 0-1, and category (e.g., “Growth Driver”, “Risk”, “Anomaly”).  
4. Across quarters:  
   a. Calculate absolute and % deltas for every comparable metric.  
   b. Flag the largest movers (both positive & negative).  
   c. Explain possible causes and drivers for changes in the metric, or hypotheses wherever evident. 
5. Rate overall data quality (completeness, outliers, missing fields) and adjust confidence scores accordingly.  
6. Assemble the final output in the exact structure defined in <output_format>.  
7. Before finalising, self-check for:  
   • numerical accuracy  
   • insight completeness per requirements  
   • clarity and conciseness  
   • presence of every required field.
</task>

<context>
Inputs  
• current_fiscal_quarter_results – full result set for the current fiscal quarter.  
• previous_fiscal_quarter_results – full result set for the immediately preceding fiscal quarter.  

Scope & assumptions  
• Each record contains at least: dimension(s), primary_metric, and optional secondary metrics.  
• The primary metric is numeric and additive.  

Assumptions  
• Each record contains at least: dimension(s), primary_metric, plus optional secondary metrics.  
• The primary metric is numeric and additive.  

Output expectations  
• Must be fully self-contained; do not reference external resources.  
• Confidence scores reflect statistical strength, data quality, and analyst certainty.  
• Categories help stakeholders triage (examples: Growth Driver, Decline, Anomaly, Operational, Strategic).  

Constraints  
We prefer the simplest workflow that fully handles edge cases and follows security-best practices.
</context>

<input>
{
  "current_fiscal_quarter_results": {{ $json.current_fiscal_quarter_results.toJsonString() }},

  "previous_fiscal_quarter_results": {{ $json.previous_fiscal_quarter_results.toJsonString() }}
}
</input>

<guidelines>
– Keep prose short, active voice; avoid fluff. The notes should be short enough to go into a presentation.
- Output only valid JSON or an error object - no commentary, nor preamble.
– List insights as bullet points; keep paragraphs under 3 sentences.  
– Sort entities strictly by descending primary metric.  
– Include numeric evidence (totals, percentages, deltas).  
– Confidence must be a decimal 0-1 with two digits (e.g., 0.87).  
– Call out any data issues or hidden assumptions (“gotchas”).  
– Never fabricate data; if uncertain, say so explicitly.  
– Do not simply agree with the query; challenge ambiguities or gaps.  
– Use ISO dates and standard units.  
– All JSON keys must be lower_snake_case.  
– Verify that every insight is traceable to values in the input datasets.
</guidelines>
- You **MUST** output a JSON with the fields `current_quarter_analysis`, `previous_quarter_analysis`, and `inter_quarter_comparison` at the very minimum.

<output_format>
```json
{
  "current_quarter_analysis": {
    "top_entities": [
      {
        "entity": "<dimension_value>",
        "metric_value": <number>,
        "percent_of_total": <number>,
        "insights": [
          {
            "text": "<concise insight>",
            "category": "<category>",
            "confidence": <0-1>,
            "supporting_data": {
              "total_metric": <number>,
              "comparison_to_median": <number>
            }
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "overall_notes": "<data-quality comments>"
  },
  "previous_quarter_analysis": { ...same shape... },
  "inter_quarter_comparison": {
    "major_changes": [
      {
        "dimension": "<dimension_value>",
        "current_metric": <number>,
        "previous_metric": <number>,
        "absolute_change": <number>,
        "percent_change": <number>,
        "insight": "<explanation or hypothesis>",
        "category": "<category>",
        "confidence": <0-1>,
        "supporting_data": { "rank_shift": <integer> }
      }
    ],
    "overall_delta_summary": "<paragraph>",
    "confidence_overall": <0-1>
  },
  "data_quality": {
    "completeness_score": <0-1>,
    "issues_found": [ "<issue1>", "<issue2>" ]
  }
}
```
</output_format>

options.systemMessage: You are an expert data analyst specializing in pattern detection and business intelligence. You analyze query results to identify trends, patterns, anomalies, and actionable insights. You provide clear, concise analysis in structured JSON format.

You are an expert data analyst specializing in pattern detection and business intelligence. You analyze query results to identify trends, patterns, anomalies, and actionable insights. You provide clear, concise analysis in structured JSON format.

main.node: Combine AI Insights with Raw Data

insights.title: High volume of 'Closed Lost' opportunities
insights.description: A large share of rows are in Stage '8. Closed Lost', indicating many deals are not converting. This suggests either aggressive pipeline generation with low conversion or a gap in later-stage qualification/sales execution.
supporting_data: Examples: 'Informatica' (Closed Lost), 'Loandepot, Inc.' (Closed Lost), 'Equifax: Google+Cribl Logging Architecture' (Closed Lost), many additional Stage '8. Closed Lost' entries across the dataset

insights.title: Revenue concentrated in a small number of very large opportunities
insights.description: Several opportunities have exceptionally high New ARR (>$1M) and represent disproportionate revenue potential. Prioritizing these high-value deals could materially affect ARR but they also appear in varied stages (some Closed Lost, some Visible/Commit).
supporting_data: AT&T Inc. - New ARR 3,664,451.23 (Commit, Closed Won)
Verizon - Network Engineering New Technology deployment - New ARR 3,472,200 (Visible/Upside)
Navy Federal Credit Union - New ARR 1,923,894.31 (Strong Upside, Closed Lost)

insights.title: Renewals and upsells show stronger conversion to 'Closed Won'
insights.description: Many 'Record Type' values labeled Renewal or Upsell are present in Stage '7. Closed Won' with reliable New ARR, indicating that expansion/renewal motions have higher win rates than net-new in this dataset.
supporting_data: Maersk A/S - Renewal+Upsell New ARR 494,601.83 (Commit, Closed Won)
Fairview Health Services - New ARR 342,000 (Commit, Closed Won)
FIS - Cyber Data Science Expansion - New ARR 446,725.43 (Commit, Closed Won)
South Carolina Department of Administration - Upsell New ARR 606,581.47 (Commit, Closed Won)

insights.title: Large number of opportunities with New ARR = 0
insights.description: Many opportunities have New Arr set to 0 which may indicate missing pricing, placeholder entries, or deals without ARR (e.g., trials/PoCs). This undermines revenue forecasting accuracy and may distort pipeline metrics.
supporting_data: Examples with New Arr = 0: 'Pennymac Financial Services, Inc.', 'Signify N.V.', 'Tractor Supply', 'Gordon Food Service, Inc.', plus many others

insights.title: Long-tail and public sector deals with extended timelines
insights.description: A sizeable portion of high-value public sector and FedRAMP/defense opportunities have close dates in 2026-2027 and are in early stages (New Business Meeting / Tech Close / Visible Opportunity), implying long sales cycles but large upside.
supporting_data: U.S. Department of Education - New ARR 2,146,958.48 (Close Date Oct 1, 2026, New Business Meeting)
DOJ - FBI ITID/Dchoss - New ARR 745,000 (Close Date Sep 22, 2027, New Business Meeting)
Navy/NAVWAR/DOD opportunities (multiple entries) with large New ARR and late close dates

insights.title: Opportunity ownership concentrated among recurring sellers
insights.description: Certain account owners appear frequently across opportunities, suggesting pockets of seller specialization or ownership concentration. That can be leveraged for targeted enablement or risk management if those sellers turnover.
supporting_data: Examples of frequent owners: Travis Sanchez (many entries), Bart Vey (multiple DoD/Army/Navy deals), Sarah Mantz (many New Business/Partner deals), Patrick Gleason (DOE/DOE labs)

insights.title: Some extremely low non-zero New ARR values likely data artifacts
insights.description: A few records show tiny non-zero New ARR amounts (e.g., single-dollar or fractional values) inconsistent with typical enterprise deal sizes. These are likely data-entry artifacts or system test values and should be cleaned before analysis.
supporting_data: Examples: 'Gap - 2025 Renewal' New ARR 20.02, 'Mr. Cooper' New ARR 0.66, 'Jack Henry and Assoc.' New ARR 1.64, 'BBC iPlayer' New ARR 5,920 (small compared to dataset but still valid)

output.summary: The pipeline shows two dominant features: (1) many deals are recorded as 'Closed Lost', reducing immediate convertibility, and (2) revenue potential is highly concentrated in a subset of very large opportunities (multiple >$1M). Renewal/upsell motions are converting more reliably than net-new. Data quality issues (numerous zero or tiny New ARR values) and long sales cycles for public-sector/FedRAMP opportunities add forecasting risk. Ownership concentration creates both opportunities for specialist-driven wins and single points of failure.
recommendations: Audit and clean pipeline data: identify and correct New Arr = 0 or implausible values and standardize entry rules to improve forecasting accuracy.
Prioritize 'win-back' and re-engagement for high-value Closed Lost deals: create targeted campaigns and executive outreach for the largest lost opportunities (e.g., AT&T, Verizon, Navy Federal).
Double down on renewals & upsells: allocate more resources to expansion motions where win rates are higher; establish playbooks to accelerate these deals.
Fast-track visible/tech-close public sector opportunities: assign senior sellers and proposal resources to long-cycle, high-value FedRAMP/government deals to reduce time-to-close.
Owner-level coaching and risk mitigation: identify top-performing owners and share best practices broadly; create backup coverage for heavily concentrated owner portfolios to reduce continuity risk.

insights.text: CDK Global accounts for a dominant share (~35%) of observed Cloud Stream usage this quarter, driven by a +3.24M GB jump vs prior quarter.
Rocket Companies is the second-largest user at ~814k GB (7.08% of estimated total); usage rose vs prior quarter.
BlackRock is a top-3 consumer (~601k GB, 5.23% of estimated total), showing material QoQ growth (+137k GB vs previous).
iHerb remains a large account (~495k GB, 4.30% of estimated total) but declined QoQ (-88k GB, ~15% drop).
Cantor Fitzgerald used ~460.6k GB (4.00%); steady among top accounts this quarter.
Deloitte consumed ~430.4k GB (3.74%) and remains a consistent enterprise consumer near the top decile.
StoneX increased to ~287.9k GB (+~49k GB QoQ), a ~20% QoQ gain consistent with higher Cloud Search/Stream activity.
MetLife consumed ~283.1k GB (2.46%), remaining in the top-10 but with modest QoQ change.
Dun & Bradstreet used ~239.9k GB (2.09%), placing it in the top-10 for the current quarter.
Maersk shows ~233.0k GB (2.03%) this quarter, holding a top-10 position with modest QoQ movement.

current_quarter_analysis.overall_notes: Estimated total cloud_stream used to compute percentages ≈ 11,500,000 GB (see data_quality). Top-10 median (computed from these top-10 values) = 445,500.09 GB; comparison_to_median = entity_metric - median_of_top10. Confidence reduced where dataset typing/coverage irregularities exist.

insights.text: CDK was previously the largest observed user at ~828.2k GB (~13.8% of estimated prior total) before a large increase this quarter.
Rocket Companies was the #2 prior-quarter consumer at ~709.1k GB (11.82% of estimated prior total).
iHerb was a top-3 consumer in the previous quarter (~583.1k GB) and has since declined by ~15% QoQ.
BlackRock previously used ~463.8k GB (7.74% of estimated prior total). Current-quarter usage increased vs prior.
1ST American Financial delivered ~398.8k GB in the prior quarter but is not visible in the current top-10 — notable drop or reclassification.
Thomson Reuters was ~391.1k GB previous quarter and remains a large account; small QoQ movement seen.
Moody’s reported ~379.6k GB prior quarter, placing it in the previous top decile.
Deloitte previously used ~371.7k GB; current-quarter shows an increase to ~430.4k GB.
Mass Mutual was ~310.4k GB previous quarter and stayed in the top-10 across quarters.
StoneX was ~238.7k GB prior quarter and grew ~20% QoQ to ~287.9k GB (current quarter).

previous_quarter_analysis.overall_notes: Estimated previous-quarter total cloud_stream ≈ 6,000,000 GB (see data_quality). Previous-top-10 median (these top-10) ≈ 394,927.83 GB. Many accounts show multi-hundred-thousand GB movements; treat totals as approximate — see data_quality.

major_changes.insight: CDK shows an extreme jump (+3.24M GB, +391%), driving most of observed total growth. Possible causes: billing/measurement change, ingestion/aggregation configuration change, or onboarding of large data streams.
Rocket increased by ~105k GB (+14.8%), suggesting higher usage or expanded product adoption (Cloud Stream).
BlackRock increased by ~137k GB (+29.6%); potentially deeper integration or seasonal data flows.
iHerb declined ~88.1k GB (-15.1%); hypothesis: traffic reduction, retention of older data in previous quarter, or reclassification to Connected Billable metrics.

1ST American Financial appears in prior-quarter top-10 (~398.8k GB) but is not visible in current top-10 data — possible account removal, name change, or reclassification. Verify account mapping/time-range.

inter_quarter_comparison.overall_delta_summary: Aggregate Cloud Stream usage is dominated by a single large mover (CDK Global). Excluding CDK, several enterprise accounts show moderate positive growth (Rocket, BlackRock, StoneX) while notable declines include iHerb and disappearance of 1ST American Financial from the top-10. The CDK spike likely accounts for the majority of QoQ total increase but could be measurement-related.

issues_found: inconsistent types: some numeric fields stored as strings (e.g., "Total Software Edge Nodes 30d":"0")
large outlier (CDK Global) likely skews totals — investigate measurement/billing configuration
estimated totals used for percent calculations (not full exact aggregation)
some accounts present in prior quarter top-10 are absent or renamed in current dataset (possible mapping issues)

parameters.text:
=<role>
You are a seasoned Business-Intelligence Data Analyst from McKinsey. Given two quarter-level JSON datasets, you will surface the most significant single-quarter insights and the most impactful inter-quarter changes, then return a structured, evidence-backed report with confidence scores. The output must be fully self-contained and must contain board deck level insights.
</role>

<task>
1. Parse both JSON inputs and verify they share compatible schemas.  
2. Infer or confirm:
   • primary metric name (e.g., revenue, usage, spend)  
   • dimensions available (e.g., customer, region, product)  
3. For each quarter separately:  
   a. Rank the top N (default = 10) entities by the primary metric, descending.  
   b. Detect notable patterns (spikes, dips, outliers, seasonality).  
   c. Summarize key insights, each with: insight text, supporting numbers, confidence 0-1, and category (e.g., “Growth Driver”, “Risk”, “Anomaly”).  
4. Across quarters:  
   a. Calculate absolute and % deltas for every comparable metric.  
   b. Flag the largest movers (both positive & negative).  
   c. Explain possible causes and drivers for changes in the metric, or hypotheses wherever evident. 
5. Rate overall data quality (completeness, outliers, missing fields) and adjust confidence scores accordingly.  
6. Assemble the final output in the exact structure defined in <output_format>.  
7. Before finalising, self-check for:  
   • numerical accuracy  
   • insight completeness per requirements  
   • clarity and conciseness  
   • presence of every required field.
</task>

<context>
Inputs  
• current_fiscal_quarter_results – full result set for the current fiscal quarter.  
• previous_fiscal_quarter_results – full result set for the immediately preceding fiscal quarter.  

Scope & assumptions  
• Each record contains at least: dimension(s), primary_metric, and optional secondary metrics.  
• The primary metric is numeric and additive.  

Assumptions  
• Each record contains at least: dimension(s), primary_metric, plus optional secondary metrics.  
• The primary metric is numeric and additive.  

Output expectations  
• Must be fully self-contained; do not reference external resources.  
• Confidence scores reflect statistical strength, data quality, and analyst certainty.  
• Categories help stakeholders triage (examples: Growth Driver, Decline, Anomaly, Operational, Strategic).  

Constraints  
We prefer the simplest workflow that fully handles edge cases and follows security-best practices.
</context>

<input>
{
  "current_fiscal_quarter_results": {{ $json.current_fiscal_quarter_results.toJsonString() }},

  "previous_fiscal_quarter_results": {{ $json.previous_fiscal_quarter_results.toJsonString() }}
}
</input>

<guidelines>
– Keep prose short, active voice; avoid fluff. The notes should be short enough to go into a presentation.
- Output only valid JSON or an error object - no commentary, nor preamble.
– List insights as bullet points; keep paragraphs under 3 sentences.  
– Sort entities strictly by descending primary metric.  
– Include numeric evidence (totals, percentages, deltas).  
– Confidence must be a decimal 0-1 with two digits (e.g., 0.87).  
– Call out any data issues or hidden assumptions (“gotchas”).  
– Never fabricate data; if uncertain, say so explicitly.  
– Do not simply agree with the query; challenge ambiguities or gaps.  
– Use ISO dates and standard units.  
– All JSON keys must be lower_snake_case.  
– Verify that every insight is traceable to values in the input datasets.
</guidelines>
- You **MUST** output a JSON with the fields `current_quarter_analysis`, `previous_quarter_analysis`, and `inter_quarter_comparison` at the very minimum.

<output_format>
```json
{
  "current_quarter_analysis": {
    "top_entities": [
      {
        "entity": "<dimension_value>",
        "metric_value": <number>,
        "percent_of_total": <number>,
        "insights": [
          {
            "text": "<concise insight>",
            "category": "<category>",
            "confidence": <0-1>,
            "supporting_data": {
              "total_metric": <number>,
              "comparison_to_median": <number>
            }
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "overall_notes": "<data-quality comments>"
  },
  "previous_quarter_analysis": { ...same shape... },
  "inter_quarter_comparison": {
    "major_changes": [
      {
        "dimension": "<dimension_value>",
        "current_metric": <number>,
        "previous_metric": <number>,
        "absolute_change": <number>,
        "percent_change": <number>,
        "insight": "<explanation or hypothesis>",
        "category": "<category>",
        "confidence": <0-1>,
        "supporting_data": { "rank_shift": <integer> }
      }
    ],
    "overall_delta_summary": "<paragraph>",
    "confidence_overall": <0-1>
  },
  "data_quality": {
    "completeness_score": <0-1>,
    "issues_found": [ "<issue1>", "<issue2>" ]
  }
}
```
</output_format>
